178
00:14:11.618 --> 00:14:12.718
[Knocking]

179
00:14:12.785 --> 00:14:14.115
[Door Opens]

180
00:14:16.023 --> 00:14:19.663
Sir. the witness positively
identified Taishi Okamura

181
00:14:19.726 --> 00:14:20.926
as the man he saw at the barn.

182
00:14:21.575 --> 00:14:23.498
along with several known associates.

183
00:14:25.498 --> 00:14:27.528
Then we have proof:

184
00:14:28.513 --> 00:14:32.040
The Yakuza have been
working with the Nazis.

185
00:14:32.610 --> 00:14:34.665
How should we proceed. sir?

186
00:14:35.305 --> 00:14:36.717
Okamura is very powerful

187
00:14:36.748 --> 00:14:38.618
and not only in the Pacific States.

188
00:14:40.613 --> 00:14:42.653
There can be no compromise.

189
00:14:43.951 --> 00:14:46.321
[Organ Playing]

190
00:15:00.633 --> 00:15:03.603
This is a sad day.

191
00:15:06.054 --> 00:15:08.138
But under our glorious Führer.

192
00:15:09.004 --> 00:15:12.448
death is no longer
a matter of sorrow alone.

193
00:15:14.292 --> 00:15:15.651
No man is immortal.

194
00:15:17.820 --> 00:15:21.517
And the life of an individual
is necessarily finite.

195
00:15:23.246 --> 00:15:26.525
But when that life is lived
for the collective.

196
00:15:26.593 --> 00:15:29.463
as Gerry Adler's was.

197
00:15:30.228 --> 00:15:34.669
that tiny seed also
becomes the very source

198
00:15:34.734 --> 00:15:39.005
of our communal immortality.

199
00:15:39.725 --> 00:15:44.536
And that is what we have come
together to celebrate today:

200
00:15:45.372 --> 00:15:47.311
Our common purpose.

201
00:15:50.751 --> 00:15:51.751
Please stand.

202
00:15:58.640 --> 00:16:00.525
Death is one with life.

203
00:16:01.708 --> 00:16:05.515
A new spring will conquer
the dark nights of winter.

204
00:16:06.068 --> 00:16:07.478
The blood of the fallen

205
00:16:07.941 --> 00:16:10.100
and the tears of their loved ones

206
00:16:10.170 --> 00:16:13.040
will enrich the blessed
soil of the Reich

207
00:16:14.133 --> 00:16:18.046
now and for all eternity.

208
00:16:20.113 --> 00:16:21.253
Heil Hitler.

209
00:16:21.314 --> 00:16:23.054
ALL: Heil Hitler!

210
00:16:30.057 --> 00:16:32.187
CHILDAN: Each cufflink is finely crafted

211
00:16:32.735 --> 00:16:36.435
with the black enamel
Gothic style letter L

212
00:16:36.621 --> 00:16:38.603
on an engraved ground of scrollworks

213
00:16:38.665 --> 00:16:39.725
surrounded by a

214
00:16:39.799 --> 00:16:41.429
delicate gold frame

215
00:16:42.065 --> 00:16:45.071
with bronze hold-backs on verso.

216
00:16:46.073 --> 00:16:48.183
These. are. of course.

217
00:16:48.241 --> 00:16:49.881
the very monogrammed sleeve buttons

218
00:16:49.942 --> 00:16:52.212
worn by President Abraham Lincoln

219
00:16:52.669 --> 00:16:56.109
on that fateful night of April 14. 1865.

220
00:16:56.352 --> 00:16:57.322
and were later authenticated

221
00:16:57.384 --> 00:17:01.794
by the President's own son.
Robert Lincoln. in 1922.

222
00:17:04.357 --> 00:17:07.302
Why are they not advertised
in your catalog?

223
00:17:08.128 --> 00:17:13.598
Uh. well. obviously. uh.
for insurance purposes.

224
00:17:14.300 --> 00:17:16.111
Insurance purposes?

225
00:17:16.190 --> 00:17:19.268
Yes. These... These would
double my premium.

226
00:17:30.150 --> 00:17:32.520
Perhaps another day.

227
00:17:37.657 --> 00:17:39.387
Tell him the real reason. Bob.

228
00:17:41.861 --> 00:17:43.161
The real reason?

229
00:17:46.627 --> 00:17:48.429
I'm Ed. Bob's associate.

230
00:17:49.655 --> 00:17:51.396
Frankly. the real reason

231
00:17:51.471 --> 00:17:53.641
why they're not listed
in our catalog is...

232
00:17:58.137 --> 00:17:59.810
it would be too risky.

233
00:18:00.089 --> 00:18:01.349
Risky?

234
00:18:01.414 --> 00:18:02.824
Uh...

235
00:18:02.882 --> 00:18:04.822
[Speaking Japanese]

236
00:18:04.884 --> 00:18:06.494
Dangerous.

237
00:18:08.288 --> 00:18:11.858
See. originally. only one
of the cufflinks was found.

238
00:18:12.559 --> 00:18:15.164
The other went missing the
night of the assassination.

239
00:18:16.311 --> 00:18:19.172
Now. Robert Lincoln searched
the President's box himself.

240
00:18:20.112 --> 00:18:22.472
But the second cufflink
was nowhere to be found.

241
00:18:23.087 --> 00:18:25.165
He spent a considerable
amount of time and money

242
00:18:25.205 --> 00:18:26.205
searching for it...

243
00:18:26.206 --> 00:18:28.136
over 50 years. in fact.

244
00:18:29.329 --> 00:18:30.329
But then.

245
00:18:30.897 --> 00:18:33.177
on the night of May 30. 1922.

246
00:18:33.625 --> 00:18:35.013
just after the dedication ceremony

247
00:18:35.081 --> 00:18:36.521
for the Lincoln Memorial.

248
00:18:36.959 --> 00:18:40.223
Robert Lincoln. who was in his late 70s.

249
00:18:40.831 --> 00:18:43.187
was approached by a man
named Theodore Kipling.

250
00:18:43.991 --> 00:18:46.456
Now. Theodore Kipling had worked

251
00:18:46.526 --> 00:18:48.656
as an usher at the Ford's Theater

252
00:18:48.728 --> 00:18:50.298
the night the President was shot.

253
00:18:50.815 --> 00:18:53.473
He claimed he found the
missing cufflink that night

254
00:18:53.887 --> 00:18:55.973
and agreed to return it
to the President's son

255
00:18:56.783 --> 00:18:58.065
for a price.

256
00:18:58.856 --> 00:19:00.565
Five thousand dollars.

257
00:19:02.375 --> 00:19:06.505
So Lincoln agrees to meet
Kipling later that night

258
00:19:06.773 --> 00:19:09.119
to exchange the money for the cufflink.

259
00:19:09.216 --> 00:19:10.846
Three days later. Kipling's body

260
00:19:10.917 --> 00:19:12.447
was fished from the Potomac

261
00:19:12.519 --> 00:19:14.919
with a rare .41 caliber
bullet hole in his forehead.

262
00:19:16.389 --> 00:19:17.819
Not long after that.

263
00:19:18.488 --> 00:19:20.860
the cufflinks had been
mysteriously reunited.

264
00:19:23.183 --> 00:19:25.672
Now. no one was ever arrested
for Kipling's murder.

265
00:19:26.448 --> 00:19:30.072
However. when Robert Lincoln died.

266
00:19:30.495 --> 00:19:32.606
among his possessions

267
00:19:33.240 --> 00:19:38.382
was a rare Colt single-shot
.41 caliber colt derringer.

268
00:19:48.255 --> 00:19:52.255
It's now time for the eulogy.

269
00:19:52.259 --> 00:19:56.229
I asked Obergruppenführer Smith

270
00:19:57.009 --> 00:20:00.926
to speak about the noble work
being done by our doctors

271
00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:03.640
on behalf of all of us

272
00:20:04.122 --> 00:20:07.313
and for the future of the Reich.

273
00:20:08.914 --> 00:20:10.811
If you would step up here please. John.

274
00:20:38.905 --> 00:20:44.635
Orator Hanley did ask me
to say a few words...

275
00:20:44.711 --> 00:20:46.181
ahem...

276
00:20:46.722 --> 00:20:48.715
on the subject of Gerry's...

277
00:20:51.518 --> 00:20:53.988
professional diligence.

278
00:20:54.555 --> 00:20:55.555
Uh...

279
00:20:57.056 --> 00:20:59.386
but I decided to go another way.

280
00:21:00.045 --> 00:21:01.629
When I sat down to think

281
00:21:01.694 --> 00:21:06.804
about what I wanted to say
about Gerry Adler...

282
00:21:09.502 --> 00:21:11.872
I realized it all came
down to one thing...

283
00:21:13.906 --> 00:21:15.036
the family.

284
00:21:18.077 --> 00:21:19.477
Gerry...

285
00:21:21.348 --> 00:21:23.348
Gerry was a family man.

286
00:21:25.821 --> 00:21:30.291
And I don't just mean his intense pride

287
00:21:30.343 --> 00:21:32.750
in his two fine boys
and his beautiful wife.

288
00:21:33.758 --> 00:21:36.400
Nor am I talking about the fact that.

289
00:21:36.831 --> 00:21:38.833
through his work as a doctor. he...

290
00:21:39.638 --> 00:21:41.628
he came to be a part
of all of our families.

291
00:21:44.270 --> 00:21:46.810
No. What I mean is that...

292
00:21:47.805 --> 00:21:53.013
a man is only ever as strong
as the people around him:

293
00:21:53.079 --> 00:21:56.379
The community he serves

294
00:21:57.113 --> 00:21:59.423
and the family he is sworn to protect.

295
00:22:02.123 --> 00:22:03.988
Whatever strength he has...

296
00:22:06.275 --> 00:22:07.692
he draws from them.

297
00:22:10.830 --> 00:22:12.570
And for them...

298
00:22:14.264 --> 00:22:16.640
he must be prepared
to give everything...

299
00:22:18.869 --> 00:22:22.635
his life for his blood...

300
00:22:25.244 --> 00:22:26.684
or else...

301
00:22:29.616 --> 00:22:32.116
or else everything he has done...

302
00:22:33.653 --> 00:22:35.523
has been for nothing.

303
00:22:38.124 --> 00:22:39.894
He is nothing.

304
00:22:45.164 --> 00:22:47.264
Now. if you'll please stand

305
00:22:47.767 --> 00:22:51.137
and join me in singing
"Der gute Kamerad."

306
00:22:53.440 --> 00:22:55.480
[Organ Plays]

307
00:22:57.144 --> 00:23:03.714
_

308
00:23:03.715 --> 00:23:10.603
_

309
00:23:10.604 --> 00:23:17.569
_

310
00:23:26.639 --> 00:23:28.579
[No Audible Dialogue]

311
00:23:49.261 --> 00:23:51.031
Thomas?

312
00:23:52.098 --> 00:23:53.198
Thomas?

313
00:23:53.265 --> 00:23:55.165
[Distorted Voices]

314
00:23:55.234 --> 00:23:56.234
Thomas?

315
00:24:09.315 --> 00:24:10.675
Thomas?

316
00:24:12.218 --> 00:24:13.948
Thom... Thomas?

317
00:24:17.857 --> 00:24:19.087
Mom?

318
00:24:23.195 --> 00:24:24.795
Let's go. honey.

319
00:24:36.776 --> 00:24:39.646
Guess the Yakuza will have to
kill someone else this week.

320
00:24:40.225 --> 00:24:43.152
Well. I'm sure that won't
be a problem for them.

321
00:24:44.551 --> 00:24:48.121
Well. I better get this to them.

322
00:24:48.913 --> 00:24:50.717
Wait. wait. wait.

323
00:24:52.291 --> 00:24:54.661
Mr. Frink got us into this mess.

324
00:24:55.590 --> 00:24:58.894
He should be the one
to... make the drop.

325
00:24:58.965 --> 00:25:02.128
It's okay. I'll do it.
You don't have to come.

326
00:25:02.710 --> 00:25:03.871
You do realize

327
00:25:03.936 --> 00:25:05.396
they're just as likely to kill you

328
00:25:05.471 --> 00:25:07.011
as they are to honor the deal.

329
00:25:07.073 --> 00:25:08.883
They want us to keep
paying them. don't they?

330
00:25:08.941 --> 00:25:10.641
These are not reasonable men.

331
00:25:10.710 --> 00:25:12.080
Yes. they love money.

332
00:25:13.310 --> 00:25:15.584
but sometimes not as
much as inflicting pain.

333
00:25:15.648 --> 00:25:17.878
particularly on gaijin.

334
00:25:19.752 --> 00:25:23.622
Well. it's better
that it's just me. then.

335
00:25:35.902 --> 00:25:36.902
[Scoff]

336
00:25:42.675 --> 00:25:44.905
You're a very strange specimen.

337
00:25:46.278 --> 00:25:47.808
You proved today

338
00:25:47.880 --> 00:25:52.380
that you may have hidden talents...

339
00:25:53.026 --> 00:25:57.061
admittedly buried very deeply.

340
00:25:57.123 --> 00:25:58.663
And the devotion

341
00:25:58.725 --> 00:26:01.248
that you and Mr. Frink show
each other would be touching

342
00:26:01.343 --> 00:26:04.030
if the two of you hadn't so
thoroughly ruined my life.

343
00:26:04.819 --> 00:26:08.066
And it weren't so futsuri-ai.

344
00:26:10.098 --> 00:26:12.196
You're growing on me. too. Bob.

345
00:26:13.074 --> 00:26:14.141
What's that word mean?

346
00:26:14.897 --> 00:26:16.306
Unequal.

347
00:26:18.314 --> 00:26:21.747
You're a grown man. Mr. McCarthy.

348
00:26:22.746 --> 00:26:26.111
When are you going to step
out of your friend's shadow

349
00:26:26.940 --> 00:26:28.654
and spread your wings?

350
00:26:29.408 --> 00:26:31.656
Me and Frank take care of each other.

351
00:26:40.206 --> 00:26:41.429
Wish me luck. Bob.

352
00:26:43.369 --> 00:26:44.699
Wait.

353
00:26:46.673 --> 00:26:49.083
You know nothing of the
linguistic nuances of Japanese

354
00:26:49.141 --> 00:26:50.581
and are therefore
liable to say something

355
00:26:50.677 --> 00:26:51.707
that might get me killed too.

356
00:26:51.778 --> 00:26:53.108
I'll come with you.

357
00:26:56.169 --> 00:26:57.917
But you gotta stop calling me Bob.

358
00:27:07.459 --> 00:27:09.059
[Man Shouting In Japanese]

359
00:27:21.440 --> 00:27:22.710
Hey.

360
00:27:24.376 --> 00:27:26.776
How long are we going to have to wait?

361
00:27:26.846 --> 00:27:29.216
SARA: The general will
be here any moment now.

362
00:27:30.136 --> 00:27:31.621
You sure that's where
he'll come in from?

363
00:27:31.718 --> 00:27:32.988
I'm sure.

364
00:27:46.866 --> 00:27:48.296
_

365
00:28:15.762 --> 00:28:17.132
What?

366
00:28:19.498 --> 00:28:22.598
You know. you have more in
common with him than you think.

367
00:28:22.668 --> 00:28:24.638
You both see me as a Pon.

368
00:28:24.771 --> 00:28:26.771
Well. since you are
telling me what I think.

369
00:28:26.839 --> 00:28:29.209
So tell me I'm wrong.

370
00:28:29.642 --> 00:28:31.772
Tell me the reason
you wanted to do this alone

371
00:28:31.781 --> 00:28:34.107
isn't because you regret
having sex with a filthy Pon.

372
00:28:36.153 --> 00:28:38.177
You know. you don't get
to decide what I am.

373
00:28:38.250 --> 00:28:39.650
I'm American.

374
00:28:40.356 --> 00:28:42.146
Wherever you were born.
you don't know what it is

375
00:28:42.221 --> 00:28:43.621
to be treated like a piece of shit

376
00:28:43.689 --> 00:28:45.879
every minute of every day

377
00:28:45.927 --> 00:28:46.964
because of what you look like.

378
00:28:47.026 --> 00:28:48.926
I grew up in a concentration camp.

379
00:28:49.392 --> 00:28:50.552
It wasn't all that long ago

380
00:28:50.600 --> 00:28:51.559
the white male called the shots.

381
00:28:51.630 --> 00:28:52.900
But not this white male.

382
00:28:52.965 --> 00:28:55.265
What do you mean?

383
00:28:56.250 --> 00:28:58.914
My family name is... was... Fink.

384
00:29:00.050 --> 00:29:01.928
I'm Jewish according to the law.

385
00:29:01.975 --> 00:29:03.437
I don't get to decide what I am. either.

386
00:29:03.509 --> 00:29:06.236
Makes no difference to me what you are.

387
00:29:07.764 --> 00:29:09.516
You can't say the same
about me. can you?

388
00:29:17.589 --> 00:29:18.929
Here he comes.

389
00:29:28.134 --> 00:29:29.844
[Chatter]

390
00:29:33.973 --> 00:29:37.843
There's a lot of security
for a grain warehouse.

391
00:29:40.980 --> 00:29:45.280
Why does a general come here every day?

392
00:29:49.721 --> 00:29:53.091
Get ready to move. Watch where he goes.

393
00:29:53.159 --> 00:29:54.529
I'm going to follow along

394
00:29:54.593 --> 00:29:56.203
like I'm delivering food. right?

395
00:29:56.262 --> 00:29:58.362
Take the trash to the
dumpster over there.

396
00:29:58.430 --> 00:29:59.430
And remember.

397
00:29:59.465 --> 00:30:02.065
look for wherever he's most isolated.

398
00:30:16.582 --> 00:30:18.482
[Speaking Japanese]

399
00:30:45.377 --> 00:30:46.647
Frank.

400
00:30:46.712 --> 00:30:48.512
Where are you going?

401
00:31:00.592 --> 00:31:03.202
[Shouting In Japanese]

402
00:31:03.262 --> 00:31:04.302
Frank.

403
00:31:06.065 --> 00:31:08.595
SARA: Hey! You!

404
00:31:10.002 --> 00:31:11.502
- Hey!
- Stay back!

405
00:31:11.570 --> 00:31:13.510
Hey. you!

406
00:31:13.572 --> 00:31:15.072
Fink!

407
00:31:15.141 --> 00:31:16.841
You.

408
00:31:17.717 --> 00:31:21.775
_

409
00:31:23.204 --> 00:31:24.204
_

410
00:31:29.956 --> 00:31:31.386
You blew it. Frank.

411
00:31:36.028 --> 00:31:38.198
GARY: If you can't follow orders.

412
00:31:38.264 --> 00:31:41.174
we're going to have a serious
fucking problem. brother.

413
00:31:45.004 --> 00:31:46.974
There isn't time for
what you're planning.

414
00:31:47.039 --> 00:31:48.869
What are you talking about?

415
00:31:48.975 --> 00:31:52.505
The badges... There isn't time.

416
00:31:52.578 --> 00:31:53.648
What?

417
00:31:58.084 --> 00:31:59.854
All right. my buddy Ed.

418
00:31:59.986 --> 00:32:01.646
he was always in the hospital.

419
00:32:01.720 --> 00:32:03.190
I was usually with him.

420
00:32:03.255 --> 00:32:06.155
In the X-ray department.
they wear radiation badges.

421
00:32:06.225 --> 00:32:08.385
That's why the Pon general is here

422
00:32:08.999 --> 00:32:10.730
and why they're pumping
enough power into that place

423
00:32:10.796 --> 00:32:13.026
- to run a small city.
- Why?

424
00:32:16.402 --> 00:32:18.872
Because they're building an atomic bomb.

425
00:32:19.835 --> 00:32:21.505
You got that from a badge?

426
00:32:22.762 --> 00:32:24.483
Not just that the badge.

427
00:32:25.443 --> 00:32:28.183
The film. In the film we lost.

428
00:32:28.247 --> 00:32:31.324
it didn't just show me
being executed by the Nazi.

429
00:32:31.324 --> 00:32:35.049
It showed this city being
destroyed by an A-bomb.

430
00:32:38.624 --> 00:32:41.534
If the Pons are building an A-bomb here

431
00:32:41.593 --> 00:32:43.103
and the Nazis find out...

432
00:32:43.162 --> 00:32:44.662
They'll wipe it out.

433
00:32:44.730 --> 00:32:46.670
And all of us with it.

434
00:32:50.036 --> 00:32:52.196
SARA: So what the hell do we do?

435
00:32:56.175 --> 00:32:57.905
We change your plan.

436
00:32:58.044 --> 00:32:59.284
GARY: How?

437
00:33:01.047 --> 00:33:03.647
We bring a plague to the Pharaohs.

438
00:33:30.742 --> 00:33:31.942
Thomas.

439
00:33:32.078 --> 00:33:33.448
Hey. How are you?

440
00:33:33.512 --> 00:33:34.512
How are you doing?

441
00:33:34.513 --> 00:33:35.913
I was worried about you at the church.

442
00:33:35.981 --> 00:33:36.981
Oh. I'm fine.

443
00:33:37.083 --> 00:33:38.183
Mom says I'm...

444
00:33:38.250 --> 00:33:40.520
I'm over-exercising myself lately.

445
00:33:40.586 --> 00:33:41.746
She's probably right.

446
00:33:41.820 --> 00:33:43.960
but I need to get in good shape.

447
00:33:45.015 --> 00:33:46.090
Right.

448
00:33:46.894 --> 00:33:48.558
Aren't you gonna ask me why?

449
00:33:48.627 --> 00:33:50.497
Yes. I'm sorry. Why?

450
00:33:52.085 --> 00:33:52.700
You know...

451
00:33:52.764 --> 00:33:56.204
Thomas. would you check
on your sisters. please?

452
00:33:57.936 --> 00:34:00.006
But you said earlier that I could stay.

453
00:34:00.106 --> 00:34:03.006
That was before you almost
fainted from overexertion.

454
00:34:03.109 --> 00:34:04.509
Let's go.

455
00:34:04.779 --> 00:34:06.109
Maybe I'll see you later?

456
00:34:06.140 --> 00:34:07.007
Come on.

457
00:34:07.113 --> 00:34:08.713
[Rhythm Section Playing]

458
00:34:12.584 --> 00:34:16.224
[Woman Singing Jazzy Song In Japanese]

459
00:34:32.838 --> 00:34:35.138
[Speaking Japanese]

460
00:34:37.834 --> 00:34:41.102
_

461
00:34:46.552 --> 00:34:48.152
[Whispering]

462
00:34:55.694 --> 00:34:56.834
Oh. God.

463
00:35:04.053 --> 00:35:06.053
Linguistic nuances of Japanese?

464
00:35:06.112 --> 00:35:07.237
What the hell did you say to him?

465
00:35:07.306 --> 00:35:09.084
I assure you it was nothing I did.

466
00:35:09.085 --> 00:35:11.177
- How low did you bow?
- Low enough!

467
00:35:31.417 --> 00:35:33.359
_

468
00:35:33.360 --> 00:35:34.511
_

469
00:35:34.512 --> 00:35:35.970
_

470
00:36:02.704 --> 00:36:03.590
_

471
00:36:03.592 --> 00:36:04.746
_

472
00:36:06.898 --> 00:36:08.628
[Muffled Gunshots. Shouting]

473
00:36:15.274 --> 00:36:16.784
Clear the building.

474
00:36:22.981 --> 00:36:24.751
[Gunshots. Shouting Continue]

475
00:36:39.865 --> 00:36:41.265
Please.

476
00:37:03.555 --> 00:37:04.555
Get out.

477
00:37:05.757 --> 00:37:07.927
[Speaking Japanese]

478
00:37:14.915 --> 00:37:19.415
[Piano Playing Classical]

479
00:37:27.045 --> 00:37:28.705
Everything all right?

480
00:37:33.619 --> 00:37:34.889
Thomas.

481
00:37:38.034 --> 00:37:40.633
He had some sort of
an episode at the church.

482
00:37:44.282 --> 00:37:45.282
An episode?

483
00:37:47.032 --> 00:37:49.342
One of the "absence" seizures

484
00:37:49.401 --> 00:37:51.941
from the medical report
that you showed me.

485
00:37:55.006 --> 00:37:57.006
It only lasted a few seconds.

486
00:37:57.075 --> 00:37:58.875
but it was like...

487
00:38:02.755 --> 00:38:05.477
it was like he died and
then he came back to me.

488
00:38:10.456 --> 00:38:12.686
He's okay now?

489
00:38:13.696 --> 00:38:15.658
Yeah. I sent him upstairs to rest.

490
00:38:16.128 --> 00:38:18.497
He thinks it was overexertion.

491
00:38:21.545 --> 00:38:23.866
But we may need
to speed things up. John.

492
00:38:26.372 --> 00:38:28.753
Oh. Julia. can I introduce...

493
00:38:28.906 --> 00:38:29.979
Henry Collins.

494
00:38:30.041 --> 00:38:33.055
You are every bit as
beautiful as she's described.

495
00:38:34.223 --> 00:38:36.284
How are you finding
life in civilization?

496
00:38:36.382 --> 00:38:40.052
Uh. very different but fascinating.

497
00:38:40.118 --> 00:38:41.748
Hmm?

498
00:38:42.977 --> 00:38:44.220
I was listening to people talk today

499
00:38:44.289 --> 00:38:46.089
about what Dr. Adler had to do

500
00:38:46.157 --> 00:38:47.890
as part of his job.

501
00:38:48.827 --> 00:38:50.497
thinking about a friend of mine

502
00:38:51.149 --> 00:38:53.972
whose lungs were damaged
when he was young. from gas.

503
00:38:54.571 --> 00:38:55.571
There's no cure.

504
00:38:58.754 --> 00:39:00.406
What would have happened to him here?

505
00:39:02.116 --> 00:39:06.010
Well. he'd be spared
any physical suffering

506
00:39:07.306 --> 00:39:11.047
and also the ignominy
of being a useless eater.

507
00:39:11.898 --> 00:39:13.946
Some people think that's
an ugly phrase. you know:

508
00:39:14.513 --> 00:39:15.889
Useless eater.

509
00:39:19.242 --> 00:39:20.562
He got death threats. you know...

510
00:39:21.227 --> 00:39:22.886
Gerry. all the time.

511
00:39:23.185 --> 00:39:24.185
Alice.

512
00:39:24.610 --> 00:39:26.825
John. Oh. good. I need to talk to you.

513
00:39:27.442 --> 00:39:29.968
Did you know that Gerry
got death threats?

514
00:39:31.870 --> 00:39:33.340
Of course.

515
00:39:33.439 --> 00:39:34.939
And the doctor that
did his last physical

516
00:39:35.006 --> 00:39:37.606
said he had the heart
of a much younger man.

517
00:39:38.610 --> 00:39:40.510
These things don't make sense.

518
00:39:40.579 --> 00:39:43.179
How can a man with a good heart just...

519
00:39:43.248 --> 00:39:45.328
- just drop dead?
- Why don't we go into the kitchen?

520
00:39:45.451 --> 00:39:47.151
- Okay? Come on.
- Uh...

521
00:39:50.155 --> 00:39:51.985
I-Is John coming?

522
00:39:55.527 --> 00:39:57.497
Excuse me.

523
00:40:02.067 --> 00:40:03.397
Listen.

524
00:40:04.670 --> 00:40:06.670
What happened is just...

525
00:40:09.307 --> 00:40:12.177
is just a terrible tragedy. Alice.

526
00:40:12.956 --> 00:40:14.883
But what if it's more than that?

527
00:40:14.946 --> 00:40:16.206
Alice. honey...

528
00:40:16.998 --> 00:40:17.998
Uh. I don't. uh...

529
00:40:18.049 --> 00:40:20.649
I didn't allow them
to cremate him today.

530
00:40:24.055 --> 00:40:26.185
You didn't?

531
00:40:26.257 --> 00:40:29.257
Because we might want an autopsy.

532
00:40:30.052 --> 00:40:31.397
Don't you think?

533
00:40:31.463 --> 00:40:34.173
Um. I'm... I'm not sure

534
00:40:34.232 --> 00:40:36.842
this is maybe the right
place to discuss this.

535
00:40:36.902 --> 00:40:39.402
How about we. uh. find one of your boys

536
00:40:39.471 --> 00:40:40.841
who can give you a lift home?

537
00:40:40.906 --> 00:40:42.836
It's been a long day. honey.

538
00:40:42.908 --> 00:40:45.908
- But we... we will talk?
- Yes. of course we will.

539
00:40:45.977 --> 00:40:47.207
Yes. we will.

540
00:40:48.714 --> 00:40:51.884
Helen. I should be going now.

541
00:40:51.950 --> 00:40:54.590
I just wanted to say thank
you so much for everything.

542
00:40:54.653 --> 00:40:57.223
Don't go yet. Julia.
I'd like you to stay.

543
00:40:57.288 --> 00:40:59.688
I would. I just have
so much studying to do.

544
00:40:59.758 --> 00:41:00.758
Stay.

545
00:41:13.739 --> 00:41:15.539
[Speaking Japanese]

546
00:41:19.144 --> 00:41:23.214
I require an explanation
for what transpired today.

547
00:41:23.281 --> 00:41:25.681
Hai. Kakka.

548
00:41:25.996 --> 00:41:27.921
Taishi Okamura was a traitor.

549
00:41:28.323 --> 00:41:29.446
He was Yakuza.

550
00:41:29.555 --> 00:41:31.638
And exploiting his position

551
00:41:31.638 --> 00:41:33.986
to spy for the Nazis against the Empire.

552
00:41:36.059 --> 00:41:37.659
You have evidence of this?

553
00:41:38.272 --> 00:41:41.828
Hai. I would not have acted without it.

554
00:41:42.393 --> 00:41:45.700
Nor without placing your
family in protective custody.

555
00:41:46.249 --> 00:41:47.611
I should have been informed

556
00:41:47.673 --> 00:41:51.576
at the same time you
made those arrangements.

557
00:41:52.235 --> 00:41:55.247
I apologize. but I had to act quickly.

558
00:41:56.114 --> 00:41:59.183
I fear you have been here
too long. Kido-tai'i.

559
00:42:00.586 --> 00:42:01.986
[Imitating Gunfire]

560
00:42:02.695 --> 00:42:05.193
Too many Westerns. [Chuckling]

561
00:42:06.992 --> 00:42:09.662
We have nothing
to learn from the gaijin.

562
00:42:10.327 --> 00:42:12.058
I admire your decisiveness.

563
00:42:12.130 --> 00:42:15.200
particularly in sensitive situations.

564
00:42:15.799 --> 00:42:18.836
as with the attempt on
the life of His Highness.

565
00:42:20.663 --> 00:42:24.609
I will ensure the clan is
aware of Okamura's treachery.

566
00:42:25.383 --> 00:42:30.620
But hierarchy must be respected.

567
00:42:32.808 --> 00:42:34.150
Unquestioningly.

568
00:42:37.623 --> 00:42:39.363
So...

569
00:42:40.057 --> 00:42:41.664
now I know everything?

570
00:42:44.407 --> 00:42:45.632
Hai. Kakka.

571
00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:50.000
Hmm.

572
00:43:11.056 --> 00:43:12.656
Prost.

573
00:43:14.159 --> 00:43:15.759
Prost.

574
00:43:17.595 --> 00:43:19.262
Pick things up pretty
quickly. don't you?

575
00:43:22.055 --> 00:43:24.567
I think you might be overestimating me.

576
00:43:25.304 --> 00:43:26.940
Mm. I don't think so.

577
00:43:31.507 --> 00:43:35.012
Thank you for your help today.

578
00:43:40.263 --> 00:43:45.718
I was... glad to be a part of it.

579
00:43:45.791 --> 00:43:47.131
It's quite something.

580
00:43:47.192 --> 00:43:49.262
seeing everyone pull together like that.

581
00:43:49.873 --> 00:43:50.757
Well. like I told you.

582
00:43:50.829 --> 00:43:54.869
this is a place where people
look out for each other.

583
00:44:03.474 --> 00:44:04.914
Julia. I don't want there to be

584
00:44:04.976 --> 00:44:08.006
any confusion between us.

585
00:44:10.159 --> 00:44:14.145
What happened at the church
today with Thomas...

586
00:44:15.754 --> 00:44:18.424
I don't know what you think you saw.

587
00:44:18.489 --> 00:44:20.029
but you're new here...

588
00:44:21.782 --> 00:44:24.470
and I wanted to make sure you understand

589
00:44:24.471 --> 00:44:27.229
how important it is not
to jump to any conclusions...

590
00:44:30.294 --> 00:44:32.238
because it could be dangerous.

591
00:44:37.141 --> 00:44:39.778
Helen. what I saw today
was a sweet boy...

592
00:44:43.749 --> 00:44:46.549
who's been overexerting himself.

593
00:44:47.038 --> 00:44:50.124
becoming emotional at the funeral
of a close family friend.

594
00:44:53.591 --> 00:44:55.331
No confusion.

595
00:45:00.799 --> 00:45:02.429
Let's drink to that.

596
00:45:05.236 --> 00:45:08.766
♪ I'm gonna buy a paper doll ♪

597
00:45:08.840 --> 00:45:12.510
♪ That I can call my own ♪

598
00:45:12.577 --> 00:45:18.347
♪ A doll that other
fellows cannot steal ♪

599
00:45:18.416 --> 00:45:22.316
♪ And then the flirty. flirty guys ♪

600
00:45:22.387 --> 00:45:25.687
♪ With their flirty. flirty eyes ♪

601
00:45:25.791 --> 00:45:26.831
So...

602
00:45:27.716 --> 00:45:28.792
who was she?

603
00:45:29.861 --> 00:45:31.361
The girl this morning.

604
00:45:33.999 --> 00:45:35.869
Yeah. she was a...

605
00:45:38.403 --> 00:45:40.373
work in progress.

606
00:45:41.539 --> 00:45:43.009
A beautiful one.

607
00:45:45.249 --> 00:45:46.249
What about you?

608
00:45:48.246 --> 00:45:50.016
Has there ever been anyone special?

609
00:45:50.753 --> 00:45:53.151
Aside from Mr. Frink.
of course. [Snicker]

610
00:45:56.487 --> 00:45:57.317
[Chuckle]

611
00:45:57.388 --> 00:45:58.488
Hmm.

612
00:46:00.191 --> 00:46:01.361
There was.

613
00:46:03.221 --> 00:46:04.497
But she's not around anymore.

614
00:46:05.894 --> 00:46:07.166
Did she die?

615
00:46:07.422 --> 00:46:08.422
No.

616
00:46:11.504 --> 00:46:13.502
She just had to go away.

617
00:46:15.560 --> 00:46:17.213
[Door Opens]

618
00:46:27.575 --> 00:46:28.845
Did you make the sale?

619
00:46:29.327 --> 00:46:30.607
[Mocking] Did you make the sale?

620
00:46:30.655 --> 00:46:32.355
[Laughing]

621
00:46:34.143 --> 00:46:34.994
Ed: So where were you?

622
00:46:35.060 --> 00:46:37.670
Out with your new Japanese girlfriend?

623
00:46:38.263 --> 00:46:39.864
Grow up.

624
00:46:40.835 --> 00:46:41.962
What? Don't tell me.

625
00:46:42.242 --> 00:46:44.202
I should be worried about my lungs.

626
00:46:45.817 --> 00:46:47.310
No. I wasn't thinking that.

627
00:46:48.851 --> 00:46:49.851
Well. good.

628
00:46:53.999 --> 00:46:55.614
- Because I'm. uh...
- Spreading your wings.

629
00:46:55.680 --> 00:46:57.020
I'm spreading my wings.

630
00:46:57.082 --> 00:46:58.522
[Childan Laughing]

631
00:47:04.089 --> 00:47:06.359
Come on. It's my one vice.

632
00:47:06.424 --> 00:47:07.424
[Ed Chuckles]

633
00:47:07.458 --> 00:47:08.458
And it's legal.

634
00:47:09.660 --> 00:47:10.960
We're celebrating.

635
00:47:12.697 --> 00:47:14.267
Celebrating what?

636
00:47:14.964 --> 00:47:16.302
Taishi's dead.

637
00:47:17.043 --> 00:47:18.043
We're free.

638
00:47:18.493 --> 00:47:19.493
It's over.

639
00:47:21.242 --> 00:47:22.565
- He's dead?
- Yeah.

640
00:47:23.012 --> 00:47:24.012
It's true.

641
00:47:24.452 --> 00:47:26.284
A new Yakuza boss will take the place

642
00:47:26.304 --> 00:47:27.629
of the late Mr. Okamura.

643
00:47:28.063 --> 00:47:30.515
but all outstanding debts
are non-transferable.

644
00:47:32.664 --> 00:47:34.050
We're fucking free. Frank.

645
00:48:00.078 --> 00:48:01.948
You check on Thomas?

646
00:48:03.348 --> 00:48:04.418
He's fine.

647
00:48:08.319 --> 00:48:11.959
Poor Alice was in quite
a state. wasn't she?

648
00:48:23.528 --> 00:48:26.098
Tell me exactly what
happened with Thomas.

649
00:48:27.472 --> 00:48:29.012
Who else was there?

650
00:48:31.809 --> 00:48:33.309
It was quick.

651
00:48:34.922 --> 00:48:37.052
Next time. we might not be so lucky.

652
00:48:39.817 --> 00:48:42.347
Did anybody else see it happen?

653
00:48:46.824 --> 00:48:48.164
No.

654
00:48:50.775 --> 00:48:52.631
I grabbed his arm just in time.

655
00:48:56.667 --> 00:48:59.167
[Phone Rings]

656
00:49:00.538 --> 00:49:03.008
[Ring]

657
00:49:04.409 --> 00:49:06.539
[Ring]

658
00:49:08.013 --> 00:49:10.283
[Ring]

659
00:49:10.348 --> 00:49:11.778
Hello.

660
00:49:11.849 --> 00:49:14.789
Obergruppenführer Smith.

661
00:49:14.852 --> 00:49:16.592
Reichsführer Himmler.

662
00:49:18.123 --> 00:49:21.133
_

663
00:49:23.298 --> 00:49:25.298
_

664
00:49:26.119 --> 00:49:27.474
_

665
00:49:28.405 --> 00:49:30.405
_

666
00:49:30.804 --> 00:49:32.804
_

667
00:49:36.031 --> 00:49:37.829
_

668
00:49:37.830 --> 00:49:41.311
_

669
00:49:41.312 --> 00:49:47.858
_

670
00:49:48.005 --> 00:49:49.269
Ja

671
00:49:50.221 --> 00:49:51.321
Heil Hitler.

672
00:49:51.389 --> 00:49:52.589
Heil Hitler.

673
00:49:55.826 --> 00:49:57.026
[Click]

674
00:49:58.963 --> 00:50:01.333
John. what is it?

675
00:50:05.136 --> 00:50:06.996
No man is immortal.

